Introduction

For this project, we will be looking at a project completed in my Bacterial Genetics Lab for the Spring 2022 semester, and my further analysis on the class project data.

Background

In Escheria coli, the MicF RNA gene controls the expression of the outer membrane porin gene ompF.

There are 10 genes used to test whether or not MicF regulate translation of them. Results are made upon making comparative observations based on fluorescence absorbency (FL/OD) between the gene-gfp control and gene-gfp-MicF. Three possible results are activation, repression, and inconclusive. If there is a significant greater FL/OD in the gene-gfp-MicF, MicF activates the gene. If there is a significant lower FL/OD in the gene-gfp-MicF, MicF represses the gene.

  • wza: produces the protein that is responsible for the transport of capsular polysaccharide from periplasmic space to surface, and the participation in the formaiton of bacterial capsules
  • sbcB: produces the protein that degrades ssDNAs, and releases deoxyribose-phosphate moeities after the cleavage of DNA at an AP site
  • ysaB: produces the non-essential lipoprotein. Function not well-studied
  • smrB: produces the protein that cleaves mRNAs upstream of paused ribosomes
  • seqA: produces the protein that modulates the replication initiation at E. coli oriC
  • hypB: produces the aporepressor protein that is involved in teh maturation of NiFe, and transfer of nickle from the HypB GTPase domain to HypA in the presence of GDP
  • serA: produces the protein that catalyzes the reversible oxidation of 3-phospho-D-glycerate to 3-phosphooxypyruvate and of 2-hydroxyglutarate to 2-oxoglutarate
  • rsmD: produces the protein that methylates the guanine in position 966 of 16S rRNA in the assembled 30S particle
  • lrp: produces the protein that mediates the global reponse to leucine
  • ybaY: produces the protein involved in lipoprotein biosynthesis and glycoprotein biosynthesis

Overall results of MicF regulation was not well presented by students in the class in my opinion. Therefore, I am performing t-tests to get better results confirmed with the calculated p-values.

Now, to make a table that display the p-values to the corresponding gene.

p_files <- dir(path = p_Path, pattern = ".csv", full.names = TRUE)

p_data <-p_files %>% 
  set_names() %>% 
  map_df(read_csv, .id = "filename") %>% 
  group_by(filename) %>% 
  mutate(Control = group1, MicF = group2) %>% 
  summarise(Control, MicF, p) %>%
  kbl() %>% 
  kable_material() %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"), 
                full_width = FALSE, fixed_thead = T, position = "center", 
                font_size = 12)

Function

Make a function for skeleton plot coding to help speed up the process of plotting each gene results.

showtext_auto()

MicF_reg_plot <- function(data = All_Genes, x, y){
  ggplot(data, aes(x = {{x}}, y = {{y}}, color = {{x}})) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    theme_hildaDusk() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 36, hjust = 0.5, family = "zen"),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 24, family = "zen"), 
        axis.text = element_text(size = 20, family = "zen")) +
    labs(title = "MicF Expression Assay",
       x = "Genes",
       y = "FL/OD",
       caption = "BIO467L Bacterial Genetics by Melissa Takahashi")
}

MicF regulation result conclusions

The overall average p-value is 0.33. Examining the results based on a typical 95% confidence level (p<0.05) would conclude most of the genes as “Inconclusive”. Therefore, I have to conclude the results based on the average p-value. I decided to examine the results based on 75% confidence level (p<0.25).

  • wza: Inconclusive
  • sbcB: Repression
  • ysaB: Activation
  • smrB: Activation
  • seqA: Inconclusive
  • hypB: Inconclusive
  • serA: Inconclusive
  • rsmD: Repression
  • lrp: Inconclusive
  • ybaY: Repression
